795
01:06:26,329 --> 01:06:30,160
“It’s not nothing. It’ll be a revolution.”

796
01:06:30,160 --> 01:06:37,550
I tilt my face up to his, brow raised. “It’ll
still be a revolution if you wait a week.”

797
01:06:37,550 --> 01:06:41,910
Father bristles at the sore spot between us.
He’s not the only fisherman headed out during

798
01:06:41,910 --> 01:06:48,269
the festival, though far more are staying
than leaving, bolstered by their recent luck—my

799
01:06:48,269 --> 01:06:55,049
recent help. But he’s the only one I care
about. And, as the royal fisherman, he’s

800
01:06:55,049 --> 01:06:58,400
the only one King Asger cares about as well.

801
01:06:58,400 --> 01:07:03,240
“There will be other Lithasblot festivals,
Evelyn. If you’ve been pelted with bread

802
01:07:03,240 --> 01:07:06,369
once, you’ve been pelted with bread a thousandfold.”

803
01:07:06,369 --> 01:07:08,170
“But—”

804
01:07:08,170 --> 01:07:11,319
He cuts me off with rough fingers on the point
of my chin.

805
01:07:11,319 --> 01:07:17,420
“But nothing. I have to seize my luck while
it’s there.” Father’s grizzled old thumb

806
01:07:17,420 --> 01:07:23,380
settles on my bottom lip. “I’ll return
for the close of the festival—the ball.”

807
01:07:23,380 --> 01:07:28,950
Despite my disappointment at yet another good-bye,
I form a tight smile after his words. “If

808
01:07:28,950 --> 01:07:34,839
you’ve seen me once in my only nice dress,
you’ve seen me a thousandfold.”

809
01:07:34,839 --> 01:07:39,369
He leans in and gives me a quick kiss on the
cheek, his beard both soft and rough against

810
01:07:39,369 --> 01:07:40,369
my skin.

811
01:07:40,369 --> 01:07:43,710
“Take care of Hansa, my dear.”

812
01:07:43,710 --> 01:07:48,359
I hug him to my chest, the cloying scent of
pipe tobacco catching in my lungs.

813
01:07:48,359 --> 01:07:52,319
“If only she’d allow such a thing, I would.”

814
01:07:52,319 --> 01:07:58,569
He releases me with a single squeeze of my
forearm. I turn for the gangplank, one last

815
01:07:58,569 --> 01:08:04,369
look at both him and my first stab at whaling
innovation. When I’m back on the sun-ruined

816
01:08:04,369 --> 01:08:09,160
wood of the dock, Father yells for his men
to hoist up the gangplank and anchor.

817
01:08:09,160 --> 01:08:15,759
Before he’s gone, and with the sailors distracted
by departure duties, I take my chance and

818
01:08:15,759 --> 01:08:20,790
press my little stone to the ship, right under
my mother’s name, painted in block letters

819
01:08:20,790 --> 01:08:27,290
across the stern. My eyes flutter to a close,
and I whisper my spell into the breeze coming

820
01:08:27,290 --> 01:08:31,250
in off the Øresund Strait.

