1379
01:54:22,100 --> 01:54:27,660
Her boot nudges the oyster bucket. “And
what are your plans for these little fellas?”

1380
01:54:27,660 --> 01:54:33,020
She scoops one up and holds it in her hand
as if it’s a baby bird and not an endless

1381
01:54:33,020 --> 01:54:35,020
source of frustration for me.

1382
01:54:35,020 --> 01:54:40,450
“They’re barren, but I’d hoped to spell
them into producing pearls to be crushed for—”

1383
01:54:40,450 --> 01:54:46,161
Annemette stops me cold with a wave of her
hand. She mumbles something I don’t understand

1384
01:54:46,161 --> 01:54:51,610
under her breath, her eyes intent on the oyster
in her palms.

1385
01:54:51,610 --> 01:54:59,630
Within moments, the oyster swells to a pink
as vibrant as the sunset and springs open.

1386
01:54:59,630 --> 01:55:05,090
Inside is the most gorgeous pearl, perfectly
round with an opalescent shimmer.

1387
01:55:05,090 --> 01:55:13,410
“It’s beautiful,” I say, though the
word doesn’t do it justice. It’s otherworldly,

1388
01:55:13,410 --> 01:55:20,260
unnatural. I want to touch it, but I’m frightened
of it all the same. It seems . . . alive.

1389
01:55:20,260 --> 01:55:27,820
Annemette’s grin grows mischievous. “Too
beautiful to crush, I think.” With a simple

1390
01:55:27,820 --> 01:55:34,280
Old Norse command—“Fljóta”—she sets
the pearl afloat over her palm. Then, without

1391
01:55:34,280 --> 01:55:40,280
saying a word, she commands a few lengths
of thread—repurposed and therefore unspooled—from

1392
01:55:40,280 --> 01:55:46,310
the nails on the wall. Next, she covers the
thread and pearl with both hands, shielding

1393
01:55:46,310 --> 01:55:52,760
from me the magic she’s clearly working
with her mind, her eyes set on her work. Seconds

1394
01:55:52,760 --> 01:55:57,050
later, her hands part to reveal a perfect
pearl necklace.

1395
01:55:57,050 --> 01:56:00,560
“Turn around and pull up your hair,” she
says.

1396
01:56:00,560 --> 01:56:05,870
I do as she says and she draws the thread
around my neck, draping it so that the pearl

1397
01:56:05,870 --> 01:56:11,950
lies at the base of my throat. I don’t own
any real jewelry and have never even tried

1398
01:56:11,950 --> 01:56:17,300
any on, save for my mother’s wedding band—Father
keeps it tucked away in a little chest, along

1399
01:56:17,300 --> 01:56:20,720
with letters and drawings and other tokens
from their life together.

1400
01:56:20,720 --> 01:56:25,950
I touch the pearl and look up at her, but
she is busy working on another oyster and

1401
01:56:25,950 --> 01:56:32,560
more string. After a few moments, Annemette
ties her own pearl necklace around her throat.

1402
01:56:32,560 --> 01:56:36,280
“And now we match,” she says.

1403
01:56:36,280 --> 01:56:41,630
My throat catches. I remember Anna saying
those words to me that time we made necklaces

1404
01:56:41,630 --> 01:56:48,760
from wooden beads the tailor was giving away.
They were crude and childlike, yet still special.

1405
01:56:48,760 --> 01:56:52,840
We promised to never take them off, but I
couldn’t bear to look at mine once Anna

1406
01:56:52,840 --> 01:56:57,340
was gone. It’s now in a small box underneath
my bed.

1407
01:56:57,340 --> 01:57:04,401
I force a smile at Annemette. My pearl sits
in cool repose against my neck, pulsing with

1408
01:57:04,401 --> 01:57:10,340
vigor. It’s a curious feeling that is not
altogether pleasant, and I wonder if the pearl

1409
01:57:10,340 --> 01:57:15,790
will always beat like this. Oddly, I find
myself hoping that it will.

1410
01:57:15,790 --> 01:57:20,200
“Can you teach me?” I ask, the words spilling
from my lips.

1411
01:57:20,200 --> 01:57:24,950
“What is there to teach? You’re a witch,
aren’t you?”

1412
01:57:24,950 --> 01:57:29,360
“I . . . Tante Hansa hasn’t taught me
anything like that. Everything I know is like

1413
01:57:29,360 --> 01:57:35,210
a recipe to make cheese—fail one segment
and the whole thing falls to curd.”

1414
01:57:35,210 --> 01:57:43,130
Annemette scrunches her nose. “It shouldn’t
be that hard.” She picks up an oyster. “Here.

1415
01:57:43,130 --> 01:57:44,810
Try. Fljóta.”

1416
01:57:44,810 --> 01:57:51,240
Annemette sees the reluctance cross my face
and tilts her head. “It’s just a command.

1417
01:57:51,240 --> 01:57:55,760
Say it with confidence and you’ll have the
magic do the work.”

1418
01:57:55,760 --> 01:58:02,190
With hesitant fingers, I take the oyster in
my hand. It’s as gray and barren as ever,

1419
01:58:02,190 --> 01:58:07,100
and stinky, too, a tinge of rot to it. “Fljóta.”

1420
01:58:07,100 --> 01:58:12,800
The oyster shakes in my fingers but doesn’t
lift. I can’t seem to make that connection

1421
01:58:12,800 --> 01:58:16,590
like I do when I spell Father’s ship. There’s
something missing.

1422
01:58:16,590 --> 01:58:20,420
“You control the magic, Evie. It’s yours.
Take it.”

1423
01:58:20,420 --> 01:58:25,730
There’s a note in her voice that’s like
a jolt—like pushing me off the dock and

1424
01:58:25,730 --> 01:58:27,690
into the water.

1425
01:58:27,690 --> 01:58:34,150
I square my shoulders and stare at the frustrating,
rotting little thing. I feel my mother’s

1426
01:58:34,150 --> 01:58:41,640
blood deep inside me. The blood of Maren Spliid.
The blood of the stregha hiding within my

1427
01:58:41,640 --> 01:58:48,300
father’s “common” façade. I feel the
spirit of Urda, outside, inside, all around

1428
01:58:48,300 --> 01:58:54,620
me, creating the natural energy we draw from.
I spin these feelings with all the want inside

1429
01:58:54,620 --> 01:58:59,990
me—the want to have the sort of power that
could’ve saved Anna and my mother. The kind

1430
01:58:59,990 --> 01:59:05,820
that can truly end the Tørhed for good, not
just mask it with a daily spell. The kind

1431
01:59:05,820 --> 01:59:08,700
that Annemette seems to have.

1432
01:59:08,700 --> 01:59:15,760
“Fljóta,” I say with all that want. With
the wound that lives deep in my belly from

1433
01:59:15,760 --> 01:59:21,420
the day I lost Anna. The day I almost lost
Nik too. When I wanted more than anything

1434
01:59:21,420 --> 01:59:24,280
to use my magic to make it better.

1435
01:59:24,280 --> 01:59:25,940
The oyster hovers.

1436
01:59:25,940 --> 01:59:32,620
“Líf,” Annemette whispers. Life. I should
give it life.

1437
01:59:32,620 --> 01:59:39,490
“Líf,” I command. The oyster begins to
change colors, its gray shell warming to pink

1438
01:59:39,490 --> 01:59:42,810
and then to the burnt orange of dawn.

1439
01:59:42,810 --> 01:59:48,210
The oyster grows hot. Hot enough to match
its new lively color. Its warmth licks at

1440
01:59:48,210 --> 01:59:50,120
my palm.

1441
01:59:50,120 --> 01:59:56,750
In a moment, the oyster pops open, the most
perfect pearl at its center.

1442
01:59:56,750 --> 02:00:01,420
It’s beautiful. Again, it’s almost too
beautiful to crush for the magical poultice

1443
02:00:01,420 --> 02:00:06,250
I’d planned, but there’s so much magic
I now want to make with it.

1444
02:00:06,250 --> 02:00:11,470
Annemette laughs. “And that, my friend,
is how you command the magic.”

1445
02:00:11,470 --> 02:00:17,570
Although the spell is over, I can still feel
the magic pulsing through my veins, a blue

1446
02:00:17,570 --> 02:00:23,670
fire so hot, it’s cold. It’s unlike anything
I’ve ever felt before. I don’t want it

1447
02:00:23,670 --> 02:00:29,120
to stop, but I know there’s a danger in
sipping from this feeling too long.

1448
02:00:29,120 --> 02:00:34,150
I set the oyster on the table I use for my
inventions, fashioned from a piece of driftwood

1449
02:00:34,150 --> 02:00:39,710
I found on the beach. It’s littered with
more bottles and vials, but I clear some space

1450
02:00:39,710 --> 02:00:45,320
and hold the pearl in my fingers. Unlike the
pearl Annemette made, this one is still warm

1451
02:00:45,320 --> 02:00:52,070
to the touch, not icy hot. The magic responds
differently to the two of us, I suppose—I

1452
02:00:52,070 --> 02:00:54,730
don’t know. But I want to learn.

1453
02:00:54,730 --> 02:01:01,390
It’s time I really embrace who I am. Tante
Hansa has kept me in the dark for too long.

1454
02:01:01,390 --> 02:01:04,400
My mother was an established healer by my
age.

1455
02:01:04,400 --> 02:01:09,300
“Annemette, will you stay and teach me?”
I ask.

1456
02:01:09,300 --> 02:01:15,170
“I can’t,” she replies quickly, her
mouth drawn tight, but trembling. She turns

1457
02:01:15,170 --> 02:01:20,440
and braces her arms against the cave’s opening,
watching the tide come in and out.

1458
02:01:20,440 --> 02:01:27,500
But I don’t understand. Why is Annemette
so upset? Why must she suddenly leave?

1459
02:01:27,500 --> 02:01:32,850
“You can stay,” I insist. “You’re
safe here from your father, and we have more

1460
02:01:32,850 --> 02:01:38,350
than enough room. And you’ll be with us.
With a family that cares for you and understands

1461
02:01:38,350 --> 02:01:42,520
you. You don’t have to run away to find
that. To be yourself.”

1462
02:01:42,520 --> 02:01:48,760
Annemette meets my eyes with a look I know,
and with every force of a Viking spell, she

1463
02:01:48,760 --> 02:01:50,670
says it again.

1464
02:01:50,670 --> 02:01:52,440
“I can’t.”

1465
02:01:52,440 --> 02:01:57,720
She bends down and runs her hands through
the sand, letting it fall between her fingers.

1466
02:01:57,720 --> 02:02:00,290
“I can’t stay here.”

1467
02:02:00,290 --> 02:02:06,441
It’s her. I can’t deny it now. She’s
not trying to deny it either. The look she

1468
02:02:06,441 --> 02:02:11,650
gave me is the one I saw on the beach. The
one that I saw on the girl’s face as she

1469
02:02:11,650 --> 02:02:17,440
loomed over Nik. Before diving into the water
and disappearing, only a tail fin popping

1470
02:02:17,440 --> 02:02:18,840
up from the waves.

1471
02:02:18,840 --> 02:02:22,690
“You can’t stay,” I say.

1472
02:02:22,690 --> 02:02:24,890
She nods, her eyes nervous.

1473
02:02:24,890 --> 02:02:27,960
“You’re not a witch, are you?”

1474
02:02:27,960 --> 02:02:30,140
She shakes her head no.

1475
02:02:30,140 --> 02:02:34,460
“You’re a mermaid.”

